                    <div class="tab-pane fade active show" id="list-app">
                        <p>
                            The <strong>app</strong> directory is where your application logic and views/template files 
                            are stored. This is where you will spend most, if not all, of your time working out of. 
                            There are a few things to take note of:
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Inside the <strong>/app/controllers</strong> directory, you'll find another directory, named "override". 
                            This directory is reserved for third-party middleware. If you install any middleware 
                            and it includes a controller that matches the name of one of your controllers, the 
                            third-party controller will take priority and be executed.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The <strong>/app/models</strong> directory is where you store your models. 
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            The <strong>views</strong> folder inside template directory is where your Twig template files are found. 
                            It is good practice to create a folder inside the views directory for each of your controllers. 
                            This will not only keep everything nice and organized, but will prevent name collisions where 
                            two different controllers each need to render a view that has the same name.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            Additionally, this structure makes it very simple to have multiple options HTML templates for your site, 
                            due to Twig's template inheritance. For example, when you first download the framework, you'll notice 
                            that inside <strong>/template/views</strong>, there are Twig files named <code>base.html.twig</code> 
                            and <code>docs.html.twig</code>. This allows us to apply one template to the main site, and a second 
                            template for documentation, by simply creating views that extend either base.html.twig or docs.html.twig. 
                            There is no limit to the number of different templates that you can implement on each site.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="list-public">
                        <p>
                            The <strong>/public/template</strong> directory is where you will store all of your 
                            web assets that need to be accessible from the web (CSS, Javascript, images, 
                            fonts, multimedia, etc). It must remain in a web accessible folder; i.e., 
                            somewhere in the server's document root (often named public_html, www or srv depending on your hosting) or a subdirectory. 
                            If you're using multiple templates on your site, you may want to consider creating separate folders for each 
                            templates assets. For example, the framework comes with two folders in the <strong>template</strong> 
                            directory, named 'default' and 'docs'. The main site's assets are stored under 'default', and the 
                            documentation portion of the site stores its assets under the 'docs' folder.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="list-src">
                        <div class="alert alert-danger">
                            <i class="fa fa-exclamation-triangle"></i> <strong>Never</strong> edit a file 
                            stored under the /src directory. Not only may this produce unexpected behavior, 
                            but your changes will be overwritten when you update the framework. If you encounter 
                            a bug, please report it. If you need custom functionality not provided by the core 
                            framework, see the "Modules" documentation on how to create modules.
                        </div>
                        <p>
                            The <strong>/src</strong> folder contains all of the framework's logic. Consider this 
                            to be a "read-only" directory. Do not store anything here, or make any changes to any of the 
                            files contained here. Look, but don't touch!
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="list-var">
                        <p>
                            The <strong>/var</strong> folder is where the system stores cache and log files, and 
                            also where your custom scripts that are run via a terminal are kept.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            It is safe to delete cache files, new cache files will be generated if you have template 
                            caching turned on; however you might experience a temporary slowdown while the cache is 
                            regenerated. Log files may be deleted manually, or by running the <code>archive-logs.php</code> 
                            file (via terminal) in the <strong>/scripts</strong> directory.
                        </p>
                        <p>
                            As mentioned above, the <strong>/scripts</strong> directory is where you will store any scripts 
                            that should or need to be run from a terminal (cronjobs, maintenance scripts, etc.). The framework 
                            comes with some scripts that you may use; open each file and read the comments for instructions on 
                            what they do and how to use them.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="tab-pane fade" id="list-vendor">
                        <p>
                            The <strong>/vendor</strong> directory is not included with the framework; it is created 
                            by Composer when you run <code>composer update</code> during installation. It contains 
                            the third-party packages needed by the framework and the autoloader. You can add your own 
                            packages by modifying <strong>composer.json</strong> and running <code>composer install</code>. 
                            There shouldn't be any need to modify anything in the <strong>/vendor</strong> directory. 
                        </p>
                      </div>
